The cleanest option is to type the component props separately and pass the generic through `forwardRef` with an explicit assertion.

```tsx
type InputProps<T> = {
  value: T;
  onChange: (value: T) => void;
};

const Input = React.forwardRef(function Input<T>(
  props: InputProps<T>,
  ref: React.ForwardedRef<HTMLInputElement>
) {
  return <input ref={ref} value={String(props.value)} />;
}) as <T>(
  props: InputProps<T> & React.RefAttributes<HTMLInputElement>
) => React.ReactElement;
```

This keeps inference at the call site and avoids losing the generic type when React wraps the component.
